novelist and anthropologist José María Arguedas’s writings inspire her to reflect on her return to her native city in movingly intimate detail. With its multiple perspectives—personal, sociological, historical, and theoretical—The City at Its Limits is a pioneering work on the cutting edge of ethnography.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aUrban renewalxPeruxLima. 0aUrban renewalzPeruzLima. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aanthropology, anthropological, anthropologists, urban spaces, lima, peru, south america, national politics, political science, protest, history, historical context, cultural studies, culture, order, cleanliness, government, governmental power, class divisions, classism, taboo, transgression, sociology, sociological, sociologists, 20th century, renewal, social life, customs, ethnography, ethnographic research.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022628097440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226280998423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226280998/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles